🖥️ Part 2 — Stress Test the EC2 Instance:
          Step 1 — Connect to EC2 Instance:
                   Go to EC2 → Instances
                   Select any running instance (launched by ASG)
                   Click "Connect"
                   Select "EC2 Instance Connect" tab
                   Click "Connect" ✅
                   (Opens a browser-based terminal — no SSH key needed)
          Step 2 — Install Stress Tool:
                     💡 stress is a Linux tool that artificially generates CPU, memory, or disk load — used to simulate high traffic for testing purposes.
                     Run the following commands one by one in the terminal
                     # Step 1 — Enable EPEL repository (required for stress package)
                     sudo amazon-linux-extras install epel -y
          # Step 2 — Install the stress tool
                    sudo yum install stress -y
          # Step 3 — Run stress test (uses 4 CPU cores at 100%)
                     stress --cpu 4
          ⚠️ What this does:
                  --cpu 4 → Spawns 4 worker processes each consuming 100% of one CPU core
                  This forces the instance CPU to spike to ~100%
                  ASG detects CPU > 40% target → triggers Scale Out
          Step 3 — What You Will See in Terminal:
                   $ stress --cpu 4
                   stress: info: [2847] dispatching hogs:
                  4 cpu, 0 io, 0 vm, 0 hdd
          stress: info: [2848] successful run
                  completed in 0s
          ⏳ Leave stress running — do NOT press Ctrl+C yet. Let it run for 3–5 minutes so CloudWatch collects the CPU metrics.
